        <div class="blog-article-body">

            <p class="blog-lead">
                Legal work runs on documents. Paralegals and legal assistants
                spend hours every day managing PDFs — redacting sensitive info,
                comparing contract versions, organizing case files, and
                coordinating signatures. Here's the toolkit that saves the most time.
            </p>

            <h2>1. AI Contract Reviewer</h2>
            <p>
                The highest-value tool for legal work. Upload any contract and AI
                produces a structured report covering parties, key dates, obligations,
                risky clauses, and missing elements — in plain English. Ideal for
                initial document review before attorney time is committed.
            </p>
            <p>
                Paralegals use this to triage incoming contracts, flag issues for
                attorney attention, and prepare a summary before a client meeting.
                What used to take 30-45 minutes of careful reading now takes
                under a minute.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Best for:</strong> Initial contract triage, client file
                preparation, identifying clauses that need attorney attention.
            </p>
            <p>
                <a href="/review-contract">Try AI Contract Reviewer →</a>
            </p>

            <h2>2. PDF Redaction</h2>
            <p>
                Redaction is a critical legal skill. Whether preparing documents
                for discovery, removing personally identifiable information before
                sharing, or complying with court orders to protect sensitive data —
                proper redaction permanently removes text so it cannot be recovered.
            </p>
            <p>
                Important: simply covering text with a black box in a PDF viewer
                is not real redaction. The underlying text is still in the file
                and can be extracted. True redaction removes the text entirely
                from the document structure.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Best for:</strong> Discovery preparation, GDPR compliance,
                protecting client PII, court filing preparation.
            </p>
            <p>
                <a href="/redact-pdf">Try PDF Redaction →</a>
            </p>

            <h2>3. PDF Compare</h2>
            <p>
                Comparing contract versions is one of the most time-consuming
                legal tasks. Two versions of a 40-page agreement, and you need
                to find every change. PDF comparison tools do this automatically —
                upload both versions and get a word-by-word diff report showing
                exactly what was added, removed, or changed.
            </p>
            <p>
                This is especially valuable when reviewing redlines from opposing
                counsel, checking that final executed agreements match the
                negotiated version, or auditing document changes during due diligence.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Best for:</strong> Contract redline review, due diligence,
                version control, executed document verification.
            </p>
            <p>
                <a href="/compare-pdf">Try PDF Compare →</a>
            </p>

            <h2>4. PDF Merger</h2>
            <p>
                Case files, discovery bundles, and exhibit packages often need
                to be compiled from dozens of separate documents. PDF merger
                combines multiple documents into one organized file, with drag
                and drop reordering before merging.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Best for:</strong> Compiling discovery bundles,
                creating exhibit packages, organizing case files,
                preparing court submissions.
            </p>
            <p>
                <a href="/merge-pdf">Try PDF Merger →</a>
            </p>

            <h2>5. Electronic Signature</h2>
            <p>
                Getting signatures on contracts, engagement letters, and
                authorization forms used to require printing, signing, scanning,
                and emailing back. Electronic signatures are legally binding
                in most jurisdictions and eliminate all of that friction.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Best for:</strong> Client engagement letters,
                authorization forms, simple agreements, intake documents.
            </p>
            <p>
                <a href="/sign-pdf">Try PDF Signature →</a>
            </p>

            <h2>6. PDF Password Protection</h2>
            <p>
                Client documents contain sensitive legal and personal information.
                Password protecting PDFs before sharing them via email is a
                basic security measure that every legal practice should follow.
                Share the password separately via phone or a different channel.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Best for:</strong> Emailing client documents,
                sharing sensitive case materials, protecting privileged communications.
            </p>
            <p>
                <a href="/protect-pdf">Try PDF Protector →</a>
            </p>

            <h2>7. Batch Processing</h2>
            <p>
                During due diligence or discovery, you might have hundreds of
                documents to process — compressing, redacting headers, or
                adding watermarks to a large document set. Batch processing
                handles up to 20 files at once and downloads all results as a ZIP.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Best for:</strong> Due diligence document sets,
                large discovery productions, bulk document preparation.
            </p>
            <p>
                <a href="/batch">Try Batch Processing →</a>
            </p>

            <h2>8. PDF OCR for Scanned Documents</h2>
            <p>
                Older case files, physical contracts that were scanned, and
                faxed documents are often image-based PDFs — the text isn't
                searchable. OCR converts them to fully searchable documents,
                which is essential when you need to find specific clauses
                across a large set of scanned files.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Best for:</strong> Legacy document digitization,
                making scanned discovery documents searchable,
                preparing old case files for digital review.
            </p>
            <p>
                <a href="/pdf-ocr">Try PDF OCR →</a>
            </p>

            <h2>Privacy considerations for legal documents</h2>
            <p>
                Legal documents are inherently confidential. When using any
                online PDF tool, verify that files are processed securely
                and not stored permanently. PdfToolStack processes all files
                in memory and deletes them within 1 hour. We never store
                document contents on our servers or use them to train AI models.
            </p>

